{{Other uses}} '''Adon''' ({{lang-phn|ê§Äê§Éê§ç}}) literally means "lord." Adon has an uncertain etymology, although it is generally believed to be derived from the [[Ugaritic language|Ugaritic]] ad, ‚Äúfather.‚Äù<ref name="DDD">{{Cite book | editors = K. van der Toorn, Bob Becking, Pieter Willem van der Horst | title = Dictionary of Deities and Demons in the Bible DDD | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=yCkRz5pfxz0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=dictionary+of+deities+and+demons+in+the+bible&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xbpiVLq2N8vmsATYsoGYCg&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=lord&f=false | year = 1999| publisher = Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing}}</ref>{{rp| 531}}
==Ugaritic tradition==
The pluralization of Adon "my lord" is ''[[Adonai]]'' "my lords."<ref name="Yiddish">{{Cite book | author = Leo Rosten| title = The New Joys of Yiddish: Completely Updated | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=V04IRE3SwmgC&pg=PA3&dq=Adonai+my+lords&hl=en&sa=X&ei=KrViVJ_bJ6THsQTLrIH4Bg&ved=0CEcQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Adonai%20my%20lords&f=false| origyear = 1968| year = 2010| publisher = Crown Publishing Group| pages = 3 }}</ref> [[Otto Eissfeldt]] theorizes that Adonai is a post positive element attested to in Ugaritic writing. He points to the myth of the struggle between [[Baal]] and [[Yam (god)|Yam]] as evidence.<ref name="DDD" />{{rp| 531}} Some theorize that Adonai was originally an epithet of the god [[Yahweh]] depicted as the chief antagonist of "the ''Ba`al''s" in the [[Tanakh]]. Only later did the epithet come to be used as an [[Adonaist|euphemism]] to avoid invoking the deity's proper name, [[Tetragrammaton|Yahweh]].
In Canaanite/Ugaritic tradition, '' æadn ilm'', literally "lord of gods" is an epithet of [[El (god)|El]].<ref name="DDD" />{{rp| 532}} However, '' æadn'' "lord" could also be an epithet of other gods. When [[Yam (god)|Yam]] is described as being at the zenith of his might, he is proclaimed '' æadn'' or "lord" of the gods.<ref name="DDD" />{{rp| 532}} In some [[Ugaritic]] texts the term '' æadn æilm rbm'' meaning "the Lord of the Great Gods" is used to refer to the lord and father over deceased kings<ref name="DDD" />{{rp| 532}}<ref>{{Cite book | editors = Cyrus H. Gordon, Gary A. Rendsburg, and Nathan H. Winter| title = Eblaitica: Essays on the Ebla Archives and Eblaite Language, Volume 1| year = 1987| publisher = Eisenbrauns| pages = 211 }}</ref> Some think that this is a reference to Baal. Other suggest this is a reference to a human necromancer traveling to the land of the dead. [[Karel van der Toorn]] disagrees he believes that it is a reference to [[Milku]], [[Yaqar]] or [[Yarikh]] or possibly [[El (god)|El]]<ref name="DDD" />{{rp| 532}} [[Ugarit]] family households were modeled after the structure of the divine world, each headed by an '' æadn'' meaning in this context "master" or "patron". Generally, this was the [[patriarch]] of the family and there may be some relation between '' æadn'' and the Ugarit word for "father", '' æad''.<ref>{{Cite book | editors = Stephen L. Cook, Jane Morse, Corrine L. Patton, James Washington Watts | title = The Whirlwind: Essays on Job, Hermeneutics and Theology in Memory of Jane Morse | year = 2001| publisher = Bloomsbury Academic | pages = 48‚Äì49|ISBN=978-1-84127-243-6}}</ref>
==Etymology==
The name of the Greek god [[Adonis]] is similar to a Semitic word‚Äî''[[adon]]'' (which means "[[lord]]").<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://library.eb.com/levels/referencecenter/article/3772|title=Britannica Library|website=library.eb.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-02}}</ref> Yet there is no trace of a Semitic deity directly connected with Adonis,<ref>[[Robert S. P. Beekes|R. S. P. Beekes]], ''Etymological Dictionary of Greek'', Brill, 2009, p. 23.</ref> and no trace in Semitic languages of any specific [[mytheme]]s connected with his Greek myth; both Greek and Near Eastern scholars have questioned the connection.<ref>Burkert, p 177 note 6 bibliography</ref>
==Hebrew Bible==
In the Hebrew Bible, ''adoni'' (‚Äúmy lord‚Äù) is always a non-deity title usually referring to a human superior or occasionally an angel, whereas ''adonai'' (literally "my lords") is reserved for God alone. In Jewish tradition, the pluralization is used to distinguish God from earthly lords and to increase his majesty.<ref name="Yiddish"/> However, many modern critical scholars see the use of a plural as a remnant of a [[Polytheism|polytheistic]] past, with the word only later coming to refer to [[Yahweh]], the single god of Judaism. It is thought that at least some biblical authors used the word originally in a polytheist sense.<ref name="DDD" />{{rp| 531}}
