{{distinguish|One Australia Party}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}
{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}

The '''One Australia Movement''' was a minor Australian political party that was active from 1986 to 1992. It was formally registered on 3 October 1986, having been founded earlier that year by [[Uniting Church of Australia|Uniting Church]] minister Cedric Jacobs. The party's policies included support for the [[Australian monarchy|monarchy]], a biblical system of morality, immigration reform and social security reform, and opposition to union strike movements.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jaensch|first=Dean|authorlink=Dean Jaensch|last2=Mathieson|first2=David|year=1998|title=A Plague on Both Your Houses: Minor Parties in Australia|publisher=[[Allen & Unwin]]|page=68|isbn=1-86448-421-7}}</ref> After unsuccessfully contesting the [[Australian federal election, 1987|1987 federal election]], running for the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] in [[Western Australia]], the party did not contest the [[Australian federal election, 1990|1990 federal election]] and was deregistered due to lack of members on 21 October 1992.<ref>[[Australian Electoral Commission]]. [http://www.aec.gov.au/Parties_and_Representatives/Party_Registration/Deregistered_parties/oam.htm One Australia Movement]</ref>

