{{one source|date=October 2014}}
A '''vardapet''' or '''vartabed''' ({{lang-hy|[[wikt:’æ’°÷Ä’§’°’∫’•’ø|’æ’°÷Ä’§’°’∫’•’ø]]}}, {{IPA-hy|v…ë…æt ∞…ëÀàb…õd}} in Western Armenian or [[International Phonetic Alphabet|[va…æda'pŒµt]]] in Eastern Armenian) is a highly educated [[archimandrite]] in the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] and the [[Armenian Catholic Church]] traditions who holds a [[Doctor of Theology|Doctorate in Theology]]. {{citation needed span|text=Members of this order of [[Ecclesiology|ecclesiastic]]s frequently have charge of [[diocese]]s, with [[Episcopal polity|episcopal functions]].|date=December 2014}}

In the English-speaking world, one of the best known of the doctor-monks of [[Armenia]] is [[Mekhitar of Sebaste]], founder of an [[Armenian Catholic]] community of monks, the [[Mechitarists]].

'''Tsayraguyn vardapet''' ({{lang-hy|’Æ’°’µ÷Ä’°’£’∏÷Ç’µ’∂ ’æ’°÷Ä’§’°’∫’•’ø}}), on the other hand, is the rank of supreme [[Doctor of the Church|doctor]] of [[Dogma#In religion|Christian dogma]] in the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] and the [[Armenian Catholic Church]]. It is bestowed upon a vardapet, a [[pastor]], who has shown outstanding educational and leadership qualities.

